//! `SubcommandRunner` trait
//!
//! The purpose is to simplify invoking a subcommand so `main`
//! can invoke any subcommand with one line:
//!
//!     `Commands::Chid(args) => args.dispatch(cli.log),`
//!
//! Instead of the ~16 lines that the default `dispatch` below
//! now encapsulates.
//!
//! Implementors provide:
//!
//! - [`SubcommandRunner::to_params`] — build the clap-free
//!   `Params` from the clap `Args` (covers both `From` /
//!   `TryFrom` shapes uniformly via `Result<_, String>`).
//! - [`SubcommandRunner::run`] — the subcommand body.
//!
//! The default [`SubcommandRunner::dispatch`] loads `Context`,
//! builds `Params` via `to_params`, runs via `run`, and maps
//! the result to `ExitCode`. Errors at any stage log via
//! `error!` and return `ExitCode::FAILURE`.
//!
//! ## See also
//!
//! - The wider CLI-args / subcommand-layer split this trait
//!   formalizes: [`ARCHITECTURE.md > args → Context + Params`][arch].
//! - Cycle design, ladder, evaluation gate:
//!   [`chores-10.md > 0.50.0-0`][open].
//! - Worked example, trait-shape decisions, naming:
//!   [`chores-10.md > 0.50.0-1`][port].
//! - First implementor: [`crate::chid`].
//!
//! [arch]: https://github.com/winksaville/vc-x1/blob/main/ARCHITECTURE.md#args--context--params
//! [open]: https://github.com/winksaville/vc-x1/blob/main/notes/chores-10.md#chore-open-subcommand-trait-sweep-0500-0
//! [port]: https://github.com/winksaville/vc-x1/blob/main/notes/chores-10.md#refactor-subcommandrunner-trait--chid-0500-1

use std::path::PathBuf;
use std::process::ExitCode;

use log::error;

use crate::context::Context;

/// Trait implemented by every subcommand's clap `Args` type so
/// `main.rs` can dispatch via a single `args.dispatch(cli.log)`
/// call.
pub trait SubcommandRunner {
    /// The clap-free `Params` struct the subcommand body
    /// consumes.
    type Params;

    /// Build `Params` from `Args`. `Result<_, String>` absorbs
    /// both `From` (return `Ok(...)`) and `TryFrom` (forward
    /// the error) shapes uniformly.
    fn to_params(&self) -> Result<Self::Params, String>;

    /// Run the subcommand body.
    fn run(ctx: &Context, params: &Self::Params) -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>>;

    /// Default dispatch: load `Context`, build `Params` via
    /// `to_params`, run via `run`, and map the result to
    /// `ExitCode`. Errors at any stage log via `error!` and
    /// return `ExitCode::FAILURE`.
    fn dispatch(&self, log: Option<PathBuf>) -> ExitCode {
        let ctx = match Context::load(log) {
            Ok(c) => c,
            Err(e) => {
                error!("{e}");
                return ExitCode::FAILURE;
            }
        };
        let params = match self.to_params() {
            Ok(p) => p,
            Err(e) => {
                error!("{e}");
                return ExitCode::FAILURE;
            }
        };
        match Self::run(&ctx, &params) {
            Ok(()) => ExitCode::SUCCESS,
            Err(e) => {
                error!("{e}");
                ExitCode::FAILURE
            }
        }
    }
}

content.text:
Your design instinct is right, and yes, this is exactly where the cycle is heading. Let me lay out the end state and the phasing question.

## What "main as pure dispatcher" looks like

End state, after the cycle:

```rust
fn main() -> ExitCode {
    CompleteEnv::with_factory(cli_with_banner).complete();
    let matches = cli_with_banner().get_matches();
    let cli = match Cli::from_arg_matches(&matches) { ... };

    let log_path = cli.log.as_ref().map(|p| p.to_string_lossy().to_string());
    logging::CliLogger::init(cli.verbose, log_path.as_deref());

    cli.command.dispatch(cli.log)
}
```

That's it. No peek match, no banner code, no `is_detached_exec` check, no bm-track wrap. main parses → inits logger → dispatches. Everything else moves behind the trait.

For that to work, the trait has to absorb **the full session decoration**, not just the load/params/run plumbing. The default `dispatch` becomes:

```rust
fn dispatch(&self, log: Option<PathBuf>) -> ExitCode {
    let is_detached = self.is_detached_exec();
    let cmd_name = std::env::args().nth(1).unwrap_or_else(|| "?".into());

    if !is_detached {
        if !self.suppress_banner() {
            log::info!("{BANNER}");
        }
        finalize::surface_previous_failures();
        bm_track_enter(&cmd_name);
    }

    let exit = self.do_run(log);   // load Context, build Params, run, map ExitCode

    if !is_detached {
        bm_track_exit(&cmd_name);
    }
    exit
}
```

And `Commands` gets a delegating `dispatch`:

```rust
impl Commands {
    fn dispatch(self, log: Option<PathBuf>) -> ExitCode {
        match self {
            Commands::Chid(args) => args.dispatch(log),
            Commands::Desc(args) => args.dispatch(log),
            // ... 10 more
        }
    }
}
```

The per-variant match still exists, but it lives on `Commands` (the thing whose business it actually is), not in main. main is genuinely a dispatcher.

To decouple `suppress_banner` from `is_detached_exec`, you're right that this design does exactly that — each is its own trait method, default `false`, independent. `chid` overrides the first; `finalize` overrides the second; no command overrides both. The coupling in current main.rs (one peek match shared) is incidental, not essential.

## The phasing snag

`cli.command.dispatch(cli.log)` only compiles when **all 12 variants** have an `impl SubcommandRunner`. We're at 1/12. Two ways out:

**Path 1: thin main at -K** (the originally-planned final substep). Each of -2..N adds one impl. -K replaces main with the thin form + adds the `Commands::dispatch` method + reintroduces `suppress_banner` / `is_detached_exec` on the trait and uses them in the default dispatch. Cycle ladder stays as planned.

**Path 2: thin main NOW (at -1), via a bridge.** Restructure -1 to also land a `dispatch_command(cli.command, log)` helper function — for ported commands it calls `args.dispatch(log)`; for unported ones the match arm holds the existing old-style block. main becomes thin from this commit forward. Each substep then *replaces* one bridge arm with `args.dispatch(log)`. No -K rework needed; -K becomes "drop the empty bridge function and inline the final 12-arm match into `Commands::dispatch`."

## The trait-shape question this raises

If we go Path 1, we're going to need `suppress_banner` and `is_detached_exec` back on the trait at -K. We **just removed them in this iteration of -1** to keep the trait minimal. Re-adding them at -K is no big deal, but the flip-flop is visible in the chores record.

If we go Path 2, we put them back on the trait at -1 (so the default `dispatch` can consume them) — and the rationale this time is that **they're being USED by the default dispatch**, not sitting around as dead defaults. The earlier "they're dead and just hide a field read" objection doesn't apply once `dispatch` itself reads them.

## Recommendation

**Path 2.** Reasons:

- It directly realizes your design ("main is a dispatcher").
- It earns the trait peek methods (the prior objection was that they hid a field read without collapsing the match; now `dispatch` *consumes* them, no hiding).
- Each subsequent substep is purely additive — add an impl, replace one bridge arm. Smaller, more uniform substeps.
- The cycle's evaluation gate is the *right* place for this kind of architectural re-scope. That's what the gate is for.

Trade-off: -1's diff grows. Roughly: the `dispatch_command` bridge function (~50 lines, contains the unported old-style match arms moved verbatim from main), plus the trait grows back to ~5 methods, plus an `impl Commands { dispatch }` skeleton (currently just calls bridge), plus main shrinks by ~40 lines. Net maybe +20 lines, but they're in the right places.

## The further-future question

After Path 2 lands, the natural next question is whether `Commands::dispatch`'s 12-arm match itself deserves to die — which is the `linkme` / `inventory` Todo. That's a separate cycle and not in scope now.

**Do you want Path 2 — re-scope -1 to land the thin-main + bridge design — or Path 1 (current plan, defer to -K)?**

That's the same shape as my "Path 2 bridge" but framed cleaner — and honestly your framing is better. The migration story becomes: *every arm starts wrapped in `sb_ide`; porting an arm to the trait means the wrapper disappears because the trait's `dispatch` wraps itself.*

## Concrete shape

```rust
// pub fn (in main.rs alongside BANNER + bm_track, or in its own
// session-chrome module — small enough to start in main.rs)
pub fn sb_ide<F>(
    suppress_banner: bool,
    is_detached_exec: bool,
    body: F,
) -> ExitCode
where
    F: FnOnce() -> ExitCode,
{
    let cmd_name = std::env::args().nth(1)
        .unwrap_or_else(|| "?".into());

    if !is_detached_exec {
        if !suppress_banner {
            log::info!("{BANNER}");
        }
        finalize::surface_previous_failures();
        bm_track("enter", &cmd_name);
    }

    let exit = body();

    if !is_detached_exec {
        bm_track("exit ", &cmd_name);
    }
    exit
}
```

Trait dispatch (peeks come back, *and they're consumed*):

```rust
pub trait SubcommandRunner {
    type Params;
    fn to_params(&self) -> Result<Self::Params, String>;
    fn run(ctx: &Context, params: &Self::Params)
        -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>>;

    fn suppress_banner(&self) -> bool { false }
    fn is_detached_exec(&self) -> bool { false }

    fn dispatch(&self, log: Option<PathBuf>) -> ExitCode {
        crate::sb_ide(
            self.suppress_banner(),
            self.is_detached_exec(),
            || {
                let ctx = match Context::load(log) { /* … */ };
                let params = match self.to_params() { /* … */ };
                match Self::run(&ctx, &params) {
                    Ok(()) => ExitCode::SUCCESS,
                    Err(e) => { error!("{e}"); ExitCode::FAILURE }
                }
            },
        )
    }
}
```

`main` match during migration (mixed):

```rust
let exit_code = match cli.command {
    // Ported — wrapper is inside the trait's dispatch:
    Commands::Chid(args) => args.dispatch(cli.log),

    // Unported — explicit sb_ide + old-style body:
    Commands::Desc(args) => sb_ide(args.common.no_label, false, move || {
        let ctx = /* … */;
        let params = desc::DescParams::try_from(&args)?;
        run_command(desc::desc(&ctx, &params))
    }),
    // … 10 more
};
```

Each future substep replaces one `sb_ide(...)` block with `args.dispatch(cli.log)`. Mechanical.

## The previous dead-code objection now goes away

Earlier I removed `suppress_banner` / `is_detached_exec` because they didn't earn their keep — they hid a field read without collapsing the match in main. **Now `dispatch` consumes them**, so they're real load-bearing methods. The trait peeks are no longer indirection; they're the API the wrapper queries.

## Two things to settle before I apply

1. **Where does `sb_ide` live?** Three options:
   - `src/main.rs` (sits next to `BANNER` and `bm_track` — small move, no new module).
   - `src/subcommand.rs` (alongside the trait — but then `BANNER` and `bm_track` move too, and that module mixes "trait" + "session chrome").
   - **`src/session.rs` (new module)** (cleanest separation; one new file).

   I lean **`src/main.rs`** for `-1` simplicity — small move, BANNER/bm_track stay put. If it grows we can extract later.

2. **Function name.** `sb_ide` is cryptic — it expands to "suppress_banner + is_detached_exec" but the function does more (banner + surface_previous_failures + bm-track wrap). Candidates:
   - `sb_ide` (your name; cryptic but accurate)
   - `with_session_chrome`
   - `dispatch_with_chrome`
   - `run_with_chrome`

   I'd lean **`with_session_chrome`** — reads naturally at call site (`with_session_chrome(false, false, || { … })`) and self-describes. Not strongly held; happy to keep `sb_ide` if you prefer.

Recommend Path 2 with your `sb_ide` framing. On approval I'll:
1. Re-add `suppress_banner` + `is_detached_exec` to the trait.
2. Add `sb_ide` (or chosen name) in main.rs.
3. Wire trait's `dispatch` to call it.
4. Wrap each unported arm in `sb_ide(...)`.
5. Port `chid` arm: simplify to `args.dispatch(cli.log)`.
6. Drop the existing `suppress_banner` / `is_detached_exec` peek matches in main (they're now inside `sb_ide` callers).
7. Update chores section accordingly.

Cargo cycle + re-propose `-1` commit message. Sound good?

